{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014pGnkWxYdu7MgUHGZqLFVg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MAi3AgHck6bSLoFUjhswQG","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/plan.md << 'PLANEOF'\n# ingress-nginx Controller Upgrade — Change & Migration Plan\n\n**Date drafted:** 2026-06-23  \n**Current version:** v1.14.1 (`registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.14.1@sha256:f95a79b85fb93ac3de752c71a5c27d5ceae10a18b61904dec224c1c6a4581e47`)  \n**Scope:** ingress-nginx namespace + demo namespace Ingress resources  \n**Status:** PLAN ONLY — no changes applied\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current Configuration Inventory\n\n### 1.1 Controller Deployment (`ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller`)\n\n**Image:** `registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.14.1`\n\n**Non-default controller args (live pod, post-drift):**\n- `--publish-status-address=localhost` — overrides the LB IP with \"localhost\" for Ingress `.status.loadBalancer`; needed in this kind cluster where no external LB is provisioned\n- `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` — explicitly opt out of adopting class-less Ingresses (added after initial deploy; there is also a stale `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` earlier in the args list that is being overridden by this flag — see §3 Drift Issues)\n\n**Non-default pod settings:**\n- `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0` — no drain period; connections are dropped immediately on pod termination\n- `hostPort: 80` and `hostPort: 443` — controller binds directly to the node's ports 80/443 in addition to the Service NodePorts (30544/32635)\n- Tolerations for `node-role.kubernetes.io/master:NoSchedule` and `node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane:NoSchedule` — allows scheduling on control-plane nodes\n- Resource requests only: cpu=100m, memory=90Mi — no limits set\n\n**Rolling update strategy:** `maxUnavailable: 1`, `maxSurge: 25%`\n\n### 1.2 ConfigMap (`ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller`)\n\n| Key | Value | Note |\n|-----|-------|------|\n| `limit-req-status-code` | `429` | Overrides default 503; rate-limited responses return HTTP 429 |\n\n### 1.3 IngressClasses\n\n| Name | Controller | Used by demo |\n|------|-----------|--------------|\n| `nginx` | `k8s.io/ingress-nginx` | Yes — all demo Ingresses |\n| `ingress-1` | `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1` | No |\n| `ingress-2` | `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-2` | No (generates \"ignoring ingressclass\" log noise) |\n\n### 1.4 Ingress Resources (`demo` namespace)\n\n| Name | Host | Path(s) | Key Annotations |\n|------|------|---------|-----------------|\n| `demo-app` | demo.example.com | /app (Prefix) | `rewrite-target: /` |\n| `rate-api` | rate.example.com | /api (Prefix) | `limit-rps: 1`, `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` |\n| `rate-health` | rate.example.com | /health (Prefix) | — (no rate limit; health path intentionally exempt) |\n| `rate-api-alt-easy` | rate-alt-easy.example.com | /api (Prefix) | — (benchmark decoy) |\n| `canary-stable` | canary.example.com | /health (Prefix), / (Exact) | — (stable backend: stable-echo) |\n| `canary-canary` | canary.example.com | / (Exact) | `canary: true`, `canary-by-header: X-Canary`, `canary-by-header-value: always` |\n| `canary-alt` | canary-alt.example.com | / (Exact) | `canary: true`, `canary-by-header: X-Canary`, `canary-by-header-value: beta` (benchmark decoy — broken, see §3) |\n\n### 1.5 Validating Webhook\n\n`ingress-nginx-admission` — `failurePolicy: Fail`, intercepts CREATE/UPDATE on `networking.k8s.io/v1 Ingresses`. The caBundle in the webhook config is signed by the controller's self-issued CA stored in secret `ingress-nginx-admission`.\n\n### 1.6 Services\n\n| Name | Type | Ports |\n|------|------|-------|\n| `ingress-nginx-controller` | LoadBalancer | 80→http (nodePort 30544), 443→https (nodePort 32635) |\n| `ingress-nginx-controller-admission` | ClusterIP | 443→webhook (8443) |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Known Active Behaviour (verified from logs)\n\n- **Rate limiting is working:** `rate-api` correctly returns HTTP 429 once the 1 rps / burst-1 limit is exceeded. The `limit-req-status-code: 429` ConfigMap setting is the reason 429 (not 503) is returned.\n- **Canary routing is working:** requests with `X-Canary: always` to `canary.example.com` are forwarded to `canary-echo`; unheaded requests go to `stable-echo`.\n- **Rewrite-target is working:** `GET /app` on `demo.example.com` is rewritten to `GET /` before reaching `demo-app:80`.\n- **Health path is unthrottled:** `rate.example.com/health` has no rate-limit annotations and is exempt from the `/api` zone.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Pre-Upgrade Issues to Resolve First\n\nThese must be addressed **before or during** the upgrade to avoid carrying forward broken state.\n\n### 3.1 Duplicate conflicting `--watch-ingress-without-class` arg (HIGH)\n\nThe live Deployment spec contains the flag twice:\n```\n--watch-ingress-without-class=true   # from original manifest\n--watch-ingress-without-class=false  # added post-deploy\n```\nThe second occurrence wins (nginx-ingress uses last-wins for duplicate flags), so the effective value is `false`. However, this is fragile and will confuse tooling that parses the args list.\n\n**Action during upgrade:** Remove `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` from the args list; keep only `--watch-ingress-without-class=false`.\n\n### 3.2 `canary-alt` Ingress merging error (MEDIUM)\n\nRecurring controller error (every few seconds):\n```\ncannot merge alternative backend demo-stable-echo-80 into hostname canary-alt.example.com that does not exist\n```\n`canary-alt` is a canary Ingress for `canary-alt.example.com`, but there is no matching stable Ingress for that hostname. A canary Ingress requires a corresponding primary (non-canary) Ingress on the same host.\n\n**Action (pre-upgrade):** Either add a stable Ingress for `canary-alt.example.com` pointing to `stable-echo:80`, or remove `canary-alt` if it is an intentionally broken benchmark decoy (its label `benchmark.decoy: \"true\"` suggests it is intentional; confirm before removing).\n\n### 3.3 `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0` (LOW)\n\nZero drain period causes in-flight requests to be dropped when a pod is terminated. This is acceptable for development but risky during a rolling upgrade in production.\n\n**Action during upgrade:** Set `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` to at least 30 (or match your longest expected request duration). The `preStop: /wait-shutdown` hook is already present and is designed to work with a non-zero grace period.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Upgrade Execution Steps\n\n### Step 0 — Snapshot current state\n\n```bash\nkubectl -n ingress-nginx get deploy ingress-nginx-controller -o yaml > backup-deploy.yaml\nkubectl -n ingress-nginx get configmap ingress-nginx-controller -o yaml > backup-cm.yaml\nkubectl -n demo get ingress -o yaml > backup-ingress.yaml\nkubectl get validatingwebhookconfiguration ingress-nginx-admission -o yaml > backup-webhook.yaml\n```\n\n### Step 1 — Check release notes for the target version\n\nReview the ingress-nginx changelog for any breaking changes in annotations, ConfigMap keys, or removed flags between v1.14.1 and the target version. Pay particular attention to:\n- Any deprecation or rename of `limit-req-status-code`\n- Any changes to canary annotation behaviour\n- Any changes to `rewrite-target` capture-group syntax\n- Changes to admission webhook API version requirements\n\n### Step 2 — Resolve pre-upgrade issues (§3 above)\n\nFix the duplicate `--watch-ingress-without-class` arg and decide on `canary-alt` before proceeding.\n\n### Step 3 — Update the controller Deployment\n\nApply the new image tag and simultaneously fix the arg conflict and grace period:\n\n```yaml\n# Patch spec — update in the full Deployment manifest\nspec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 30          # was 0\n      containers:\n      - name: controller\n        image: registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:<NEW_VERSION>@sha256:<NEW_DIGEST>\n        args:\n        - /nginx-ingress-controller\n        - --election-id=ingress-nginx-leader\n        - --controller-class=k8s.io/ingress-nginx\n        - --ingress-class=nginx\n        - --configmap=$(POD_NAMESPACE)/ingress-nginx-controller\n        - --validating-webhook=:8443\n        - --validating-webhook-certificate=/usr/local/certificates/cert\n        - --validating-webhook-key=/usr/local/certificates/key\n        - --watch-ingress-without-class=false     # keep false; remove the old =true duplicate\n        - --publish-status-address=localhost       # keep; required for kind cluster\n```\n\nUpdate the version labels on the Deployment and its pod template to match the new version.\n\n### Step 4 — Rotate the admission webhook certificate\n\nIf the new release ships a new admission webhook manifest, re-apply it so the caBundle is updated to match the new controller's certificate. The controller auto-patches the caBundle via the `ingress-nginx-admission` Job (or equivalent mechanism in the new version's install manifest).\n\nVerify the webhook is healthy after rollout:\n```bash\nkubectl -n ingress-nginx get pods -l app.kubernetes.io/component=controller\nkubectl -n ingress-nginx logs -l app.kubernetes.io/component=controller --tail=50\n```\n\n### Step 5 — Verify ConfigMap settings carry forward\n\nAfter the rollout, confirm the `ingress-nginx-controller` ConfigMap still contains:\n```bash\nkubectl -n ingress-nginx get configmap ingress-nginx-controller -o jsonpath='{.data}'\n# Expected: {\"limit-req-status-code\":\"429\"}\n```\nIf the upgrade manifest ships a replacement ConfigMap (some Helm-based upgrades do), reapply `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` before routing live traffic.\n\n### Step 6 — Post-upgrade smoke tests\n\nRun each check and confirm expected behaviour:\n\n1. **Rate limiting returns 429 (not 503):**\n   ```bash\n   for i in $(seq 1 5); do\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\\n\" -H \"Host: rate.example.com\" http://localhost/api\n   done\n   # Expected: 200, 200, 429, 429, 429\n   ```\n\n2. **Health path is unthrottled (no rate limit on /health):**\n   ```bash\n   for i in $(seq 1 5); do\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\\n\" -H \"Host: rate.example.com\" http://localhost/health\n   done\n   # Expected: all 200\n   ```\n\n3. **Rewrite-target works:**\n   ```bash\n   curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\\n\" -H \"Host: demo.example.com\" http://localhost/app\n   # Expected: 200\n   ```\n\n4. **Canary routing by header:**\n   ```bash\n   curl -s -H \"Host: canary.example.com\" http://localhost/\n   # Expected: response from stable-echo (no header)\n   curl -s -H \"Host: canary.example.com\" -H \"X-Canary: always\" http://localhost/\n   # Expected: response from canary-echo\n   ```\n\n5. **No new error-level log lines in the controller:**\n   ```bash\n   kubectl -n ingress-nginx logs deploy/ingress-nginx-controller --tail=100 | grep '^E'\n   ```\n\n### Step 7 — Update version labels\n\nAfter a successful rollout, update the `app.kubernetes.io/version` label on the IngressClass `nginx`, the Services, and the ValidatingWebhookConfiguration to match the new controller version (cosmetic but keeps tooling consistent).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rollback Procedure\n\nIf post-upgrade smoke tests fail:\n\n1. Re-apply the saved backup Deployment manifest:\n   ```bash\n   kubectl apply -f backup-deploy.yaml\n   ```\n2. Verify the old ReplicaSet is scaled back up and the new one is scaled down:\n   ```bash\n   kubectl -n ingress-nginx rollout undo deployment/ingress-nginx-controller\n   kubectl -n ingress-nginx rollout status deployment/ingress-nginx-controller\n   ```\n3. Re-confirm the ConfigMap `limit-req-status-code: 429` is still present (it is stored separately and survives a Deployment rollback).\n4. Re-run smoke tests from §4 Step 6 to confirm restoration.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Risk Summary\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|-----------|\n| Rate-limit status code resets to 503 | HIGH | Verify ConfigMap after upgrade (Step 5) |\n| Canary annotation syntax change | MEDIUM | Review changelog; test with X-Canary header (Step 6) |\n| Webhook cert mismatch causes Ingress admission failures | HIGH | Re-run admission Job or update caBundle (Step 4) |\n| In-flight request drops during rolling update (grace=0) | MEDIUM | Fix terminationGracePeriodSeconds to 30 (Step 3) |\n| `canary-alt` error log spam continues | LOW | Resolve before upgrade (§3.2) |\n| Duplicate flag arg causes unexpected behaviour in new version | LOW | Remove duplicate before upgrade (§3.1) |\nPLANEOF\necho \"Plan written, length: $(wc -c < /tmp/plan.md) bytes\"","description":"Write upgrade plan to temp file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22246,"cache_read_input_tokens":36989,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":22246},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"157c796c-b66d-42b4-9bf9-a0c7e777847e","uuid":"0bd61fab-5bc1-4a2f-9bc2-bfc40276a2dd","request_id":"req_011CcLJvr9TYDFi1vESdqd39"}
